The grammar can start a derivation only in one of two ways:

1. S → NT4 NT1  
   – NT1 is only produced directly by a single terminal (there are no binary rules for NT1).  
   – Therefore the last symbol of the string would have to be one of the terminals that produce NT1 (t28, t15, t40, t68, t84, t24, t37, t26, t91).  
   – The given string ends with t63, so this start rule cannot generate the string.

2. S → NT8 NT7  
   – NT7 can be produced either directly by a single terminal (t17, t19, t9, t26, t30, t34, t38, t82, t99) or by the binary rule NT7 → NT2 NT4.  
   – The only terminal of the string that yields NT7 directly is t82, which is the eighth symbol, not the last.  
   – To use the binary rule NT7 → NT2 NT4 the final terminal would have to yield NT4, but t63 only yields NT6. No combination of the last two or three symbols can give NT2 NT4 either.  
   – Hence the suffix of the string cannot yield NT7, so this start rule also fails.

Since neither initial production of S can match the string, the grammar does not generate it.

No

The start symbol S can only be produced in one of two ways

1. S → NT8 NT7
2. S → NT4 NT1

Therefore the final string must be split into two contiguous parts where  

• the left part is generated by NT8 (or NT4) and  
• the right part is generated by NT7 (or NT1) and covers the very last token of the string.

Look at the last token of the given string:

token 23 = t18 → { NT0 }     (no other non-terminal derives t18)

Now check the possibilities for the required right-hand non-terminal:

•  NT1 is obtained only from single tokens whose value is one of
  t28, t15, t68, t26, t24, t37, t40, t84, t91 …
  Since t18 is not on that list, the suffix cannot be an NT1.

•  NT7 can be obtained
   – directly from the single terminals t17, t19, t26, t30, t34, t38, t82, t9, t99, or  
   – by the binary rule NT7 → NT2 NT4.
  Again, t18 is not one of NT7’s single-token terminals, so the only hope is
  NT7 → NT2 NT4 with the substring ending in t18.

  But in NT7 → NT2 NT4 the rightmost symbol of the substring is produced by NT4.
  NT4, however, is produced either by one of the terminals
  t69, t57, t22, t61, t55, t41, t5
  or by the rule NT4 → NT0 NT8 (whose rightmost symbol is in NT8).
  None of those possibilities can produce a final token t18 (which is only NT0).
  Hence a substring ending in t18 can never be an NT4, so it can never be an NT7.

Since the required right-hand non-terminal (NT1 or NT7) cannot cover the last
token t18, neither of the two start rules can generate the entire string.

Consequently the given grammar does not generate the string.

No
